WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.602 --> 00:00:03.352
(ambient music)

2
00:00:07.950 --> 00:00:10.590
<v Host>Dr. Holt is back, of course.</v>

3
00:00:10.590 --> 00:00:11.880
We're gonna talk about hematology.

4
00:00:11.880 --> 00:00:12.780
Thank you, ma'am.

5
00:00:12.780 --> 00:00:13.740
<v ->Awesome.</v>

6
00:00:13.740 --> 00:00:14.970
All right, this is a fun talk.

7
00:00:14.970 --> 00:00:16.020
I always love this talk

8
00:00:16.020 --> 00:00:17.970
because I feel like this has changed a lot

9
00:00:17.970 --> 00:00:20.730
over the last five to 10 years, hematology.

10
00:00:20.730 --> 00:00:22.410
Unfortunately, nothing exciting

11
00:00:22.410 --> 00:00:23.460
happened to me over the break.

12
00:00:23.460 --> 00:00:25.680
I still have no disclosures.

13
00:00:25.680 --> 00:00:27.030
What are we gonna spend time on today?

14
00:00:27.030 --> 00:00:28.890
A fair bit of time on anemia.

15
00:00:28.890 --> 00:00:31.470
A wee little bit of time on sickle cell,

16
00:00:31.470 --> 00:00:34.830
TTP, leukemia, hemophilia, multiple myeloma.

17
00:00:34.830 --> 00:00:37.110
Just those real quick bullet points again.

18
00:00:37.110 --> 00:00:39.810
And then the most of our time on DVT and PE

19
00:00:39.810 --> 00:00:42.090
and a little bit on what to do if they're pregnant person

20
00:00:42.090 --> 00:00:43.533
with DVT and PE.

21
00:00:44.370 --> 00:00:45.810
So you're gonna see a lot of this.

22
00:00:45.810 --> 00:00:47.610
Obviously, all of you have seen this before.

23
00:00:47.610 --> 00:00:49.290
You're gonna continue to see this.

24
00:00:49.290 --> 00:00:53.190
2/3 of the time, it will be a DVT, 1/3 a PE.

25
00:00:53.190 --> 00:00:54.720
And oftentimes they go together, right?

26
00:00:54.720 --> 00:00:57.480
So if you have a proximal DVT, 40% chance,

27
00:00:57.480 --> 00:01:00.630
you also have a PE at the time of diagnosis.

28
00:01:00.630 --> 00:01:03.570
70% of those with PE also have a DVT

29
00:01:03.570 --> 00:01:06.840
at the time of diagnosis if you go looking for it.

30
00:01:06.840 --> 00:01:09.390
Mortality rates are 6% with the DVT.

31
00:01:09.390 --> 00:01:10.440
I always think that's interesting.

32
00:01:10.440 --> 00:01:12.180
What the heck are they dying from?

33
00:01:12.180 --> 00:01:14.670
Well, if you look at the incidents, they die

34
00:01:14.670 --> 00:01:16.470
because they progress to a PE

35
00:01:16.470 --> 00:01:18.270
or from some of their other comorbidities.

36
00:01:18.270 --> 00:01:19.560
They're old, they have cancer

37
00:01:19.560 --> 00:01:21.240
and they have cardiovascular disease.

38
00:01:21.240 --> 00:01:23.730
So it's some of those comorbidities contributing.

39
00:01:23.730 --> 00:01:26.580
But PE stands alone as a 12% mortality.

40
00:01:26.580 --> 00:01:28.710
So pretty darn high.

41
00:01:28.710 --> 00:01:32.580
Dr. Virchow was making this happen in long, long time ago,

42
00:01:32.580 --> 00:01:34.140
and it's still valid to this day.

43
00:01:34.140 --> 00:01:35.160
So way to go for him.

44
00:01:35.160 --> 00:01:38.670
Stasis, hypercoagulability, endothelial injury.

45
00:01:38.670 --> 00:01:42.180
We have added to Dr. Virchow's list with a few things here.

46
00:01:42.180 --> 00:01:44.280
So male gender is difference in this.

47
00:01:44.280 --> 00:01:46.257
As you know, Dr. Connor pointed out,

48
00:01:46.257 --> 00:01:47.130
and it doesn't matter in a lot of medicine.

49
00:01:47.130 --> 00:01:48.780
It does matter here.

50
00:01:48.780 --> 00:01:50.310
Family history, thrombophilia

51
00:01:50.310 --> 00:01:52.080
is a really important risk factor.

52
00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:53.130
Obesity, right?

53
00:01:53.130 --> 00:01:55.770
We know we're in this epidemic of obesity right now.

54
00:01:55.770 --> 00:02:00.120
So we're seeing more and more blood clots these days.

55
00:02:00.120 --> 00:02:01.500
Also for the really thin people,

56
00:02:01.500 --> 00:02:03.450
those are usually cancer patients though.

57
00:02:03.450 --> 00:02:05.490
That's why they have a higher incidence.

58
00:02:05.490 --> 00:02:07.800
Prior history of it certainly increases it.

59
00:02:07.800 --> 00:02:10.320
Cancer, as we mentioned, stroke, pregnancy,

60
00:02:10.320 --> 00:02:12.330
and of course, COVID has been added to the list.

61
00:02:12.330 --> 00:02:14.550
So we'll talk about that briefly.

62
00:02:14.550 --> 00:02:17.580
The Well's criteria is still a really valid tool.

63
00:02:17.580 --> 00:02:19.530
Hopefully, you all have it on your MD calc.

64
00:02:19.530 --> 00:02:21.000
When you see a patient in the office

65
00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:23.010
and you can just calculate them right up.

66
00:02:23.010 --> 00:02:24.720
But here are the point systems.

67
00:02:24.720 --> 00:02:25.800
I love that last one.

68
00:02:25.800 --> 00:02:28.500
You know, alternative diagnosis is more likely.

69
00:02:28.500 --> 00:02:30.420
If they have a unilateral swollen ankle

70
00:02:30.420 --> 00:02:32.700
'cause they just sprang their ankle, right?

71
00:02:32.700 --> 00:02:34.770
You're not gonna think as much of a DVT there.

72
00:02:34.770 --> 00:02:38.400
You're gonna pull that back with those minus two points.

73
00:02:38.400 --> 00:02:39.660
As you've added up your points,

74
00:02:39.660 --> 00:02:41.700
you wanna know what are their risks.

75
00:02:41.700 --> 00:02:43.590
Zero, low risk.

76
00:02:43.590 --> 00:02:45.180
Three or more points, high risk.

77
00:02:45.180 --> 00:02:47.130
That's all you need to know there.

78
00:02:47.130 --> 00:02:48.980
So let's get into our first question.

79
00:02:49.830 --> 00:02:51.690
38-year-old female patient presents

80
00:02:51.690 --> 00:02:54.540
with pain in her right calf of three days duration.

81
00:02:54.540 --> 00:02:58.080
She had a lap coli eight weeks ago, cervical colonization

82
00:02:58.080 --> 00:03:01.920
for carcinoma in situ two, six years ago with no recurrence.

83
00:03:01.920 --> 00:03:03.750
No one in her family has had a clot.

84
00:03:03.750 --> 00:03:06.570
She has two plus bilateral ankle edema.

85
00:03:06.570 --> 00:03:08.880
What's your initial diagnostic study?

86
00:03:08.880 --> 00:03:11.880
D-dimer, protein C and S,

87
00:03:11.880 --> 00:03:14.853
venous compression ultrasounds or a venogram?

88
00:03:19.750 --> 00:03:21.450
Okay, so we had some debate here.

89
00:03:21.450 --> 00:03:24.000
D-dimer or venous compression ultrasound.

90
00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:24.900
I'm glad we're here.

91
00:03:24.900 --> 00:03:27.570
We have a little bit of a learning opportunity.

92
00:03:27.570 --> 00:03:32.040
So the D-dimer is a really great test for kind of one thing.

93
00:03:32.040 --> 00:03:34.440
It has excellent negative predictive value.

94
00:03:34.440 --> 00:03:36.750
So 95% negative predictive value.

95
00:03:36.750 --> 00:03:39.540
So if you have a negative D-dimer,

96
00:03:39.540 --> 00:03:40.413
you can really speak highly

97
00:03:40.413 --> 00:03:42.750
that that person does not have a clot.

98
00:03:42.750 --> 00:03:44.310
Unfortunately, most patients end up

99
00:03:44.310 --> 00:03:45.690
with a little positive D-dimer,

100
00:03:45.690 --> 00:03:46.950
especially if they're in the ER

101
00:03:46.950 --> 00:03:48.780
and then you're not sure what to do.

102
00:03:48.780 --> 00:03:50.820
But this is an important test.

103
00:03:50.820 --> 00:03:52.800
As you get older, everybody's D-dimer

104
00:03:52.800 --> 00:03:54.810
gets a little more mature as well, I'll say.

105
00:03:54.810 --> 00:03:58.200
And so you can consider age times 10 for those over 50

106
00:03:58.200 --> 00:03:59.550
as a better cutoff

107
00:03:59.550 --> 00:04:02.253
because of that increased false positive with age.

108
00:04:04.020 --> 00:04:06.360
So if you have a normal D-dimer

109
00:04:06.360 --> 00:04:08.520
and a low probability Well score,

110
00:04:08.520 --> 00:04:11.230
which our patient did in this question, your

111
00:04:12.140 --> 00:04:13.620
your DVT is very unlikely.

112
00:04:13.620 --> 00:04:15.540
You do not need any additional testing.

113
00:04:15.540 --> 00:04:17.555
So that's why you wouldn't have done

114
00:04:17.555 --> 00:04:18.780
venous compression ultrasound in her

115
00:04:18.780 --> 00:04:20.220
because she was low probability.

116
00:04:20.220 --> 00:04:22.770
So your D-dimer is super helpful.

117
00:04:22.770 --> 00:04:24.060
If you have a moderate

118
00:04:24.060 --> 00:04:27.330
or high pretest probability with your Well's score,

119
00:04:27.330 --> 00:04:30.240
just skip the D-dimer and go right to the ultrasounds.

120
00:04:30.240 --> 00:04:31.073
Okay?

121
00:04:31.073 --> 00:04:33.960
So that's why that one in this question was the way it was.

122
00:04:33.960 --> 00:04:35.550
Ultrasounds are pretty great for this.

123
00:04:35.550 --> 00:04:39.180
Look at that positive predictive value, 94%.

124
00:04:39.180 --> 00:04:41.070
But if they're negative and you're just shocked,

125
00:04:41.070 --> 00:04:42.210
you're like, "You gotta be kidding me.

126
00:04:42.210 --> 00:04:44.310
I really thought that'd be positive."

127
00:04:44.310 --> 00:04:47.073
You can opt to test them again in five to seven days.

128
00:04:48.090 --> 00:04:49.440
It has the best sensitivity

129
00:04:49.440 --> 00:04:52.650
and specificity for more proximal disease.

130
00:04:52.650 --> 00:04:55.200
It gets worse the lower down you go.

131
00:04:55.200 --> 00:04:56.580
And there are some limitations.

132
00:04:56.580 --> 00:04:58.590
It won't tell you newer old clot.

133
00:04:58.590 --> 00:05:03.240
Sometimes, abscesses or infection can trick it a little bit.

134
00:05:03.240 --> 00:05:06.357
So be aware that it's not, you know, 100%.

135
00:05:06.357 --> 00:05:08.250
This is a common question that we get clinically

136
00:05:08.250 --> 00:05:10.110
and sometimes on the boards too.

137
00:05:10.110 --> 00:05:11.700
So if you diagnose that clot,

138
00:05:11.700 --> 00:05:13.560
who do we need to go hunting for things on?

139
00:05:13.560 --> 00:05:14.460
Who has cancer?

140
00:05:14.460 --> 00:05:15.930
Who has something in their family history

141
00:05:15.930 --> 00:05:17.430
that's a hemophilia?

142
00:05:17.430 --> 00:05:19.770
So we've got some good data on this now.

143
00:05:19.770 --> 00:05:21.840
Screening for malignancy.

144
00:05:21.840 --> 00:05:26.640
Cancer risk is 1.3 times expected, not 78 times expected,

145
00:05:26.640 --> 00:05:28.950
which is maybe like what was in my brain initially.

146
00:05:28.950 --> 00:05:31.413
It's a little higher, but it's not crazy high.

147
00:05:32.370 --> 00:05:33.390
Do your history and physical.

148
00:05:33.390 --> 00:05:35.040
Do what you already know how to do.

149
00:05:35.040 --> 00:05:36.660
Do routine cancer screenings

150
00:05:36.660 --> 00:05:39.450
but don't go on this big aggressive cancer hunt

151
00:05:39.450 --> 00:05:41.580
because usually, cancer is gonna present itself

152
00:05:41.580 --> 00:05:43.890
in another way before you get that first clot.

153
00:05:43.890 --> 00:05:46.140
And this is now strength the recommendation A

154
00:05:46.140 --> 00:05:47.640
coming out of AFP.

155
00:05:47.640 --> 00:05:51.420
Just do routine age appropriate cancer screens.

156
00:05:51.420 --> 00:05:53.460
If you are gonna have that link,

157
00:05:53.460 --> 00:05:55.380
stage four cancer has much higher risk

158
00:05:55.380 --> 00:05:58.680
of clotting regardless of cancer origination.

159
00:05:58.680 --> 00:06:01.830
Myeloproliferative is a really big hot player for clots.

160
00:06:01.830 --> 00:06:04.050
So if you have a patient with myeloproliferative disease,

161
00:06:04.050 --> 00:06:06.030
and we'll talk about that a little later,

162
00:06:06.030 --> 00:06:08.760
anticoagulation is important process for them.

163
00:06:08.760 --> 00:06:11.163
Lungs, ovary, brain, other big players.

164
00:06:12.660 --> 00:06:14.670
Who needs screening for thrombophilia?

165
00:06:14.670 --> 00:06:16.567
Another strength of recommendation A says,

166
00:06:16.567 --> 00:06:18.330
"Relax, don't get it on everybody,"

167
00:06:18.330 --> 00:06:20.880
which is good advice, but who does need it?

168
00:06:20.880 --> 00:06:23.130
If you're young when you first have that clot,

169
00:06:23.130 --> 00:06:24.750
age prior to 50.

170
00:06:24.750 --> 00:06:26.460
If you do have that family history,

171
00:06:26.460 --> 00:06:28.110
if you've had another clot before

172
00:06:28.110 --> 00:06:31.230
and you're coming up on number two, maybe consider it.

173
00:06:31.230 --> 00:06:33.090
What if you have an unusual vascular bed?

174
00:06:33.090 --> 00:06:36.000
That means it's not in an arm or leg, it's in a gut.

175
00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:37.140
It's in a brain.

176
00:06:37.140 --> 00:06:39.450
You might wanna think about thrombophilia workup.

177
00:06:39.450 --> 00:06:41.790
And you also wanna put myeloproliferative disease

178
00:06:41.790 --> 00:06:42.623
in your brain too

179
00:06:42.623 --> 00:06:44.850
'cause that's a really hot link for that one.

180
00:06:45.720 --> 00:06:47.790
Warfarin-induced Coumadin skin necrosis.

181
00:06:47.790 --> 00:06:49.380
We've kind of heard about that for a long time.

182
00:06:49.380 --> 00:06:51.270
Hopefully, we're not seeing much of that these days

183
00:06:51.270 --> 00:06:52.770
'cause we understand how important it is

184
00:06:52.770 --> 00:06:55.440
to bridge them with Lovenox.

185
00:06:55.440 --> 00:06:58.800
But we know then that they could have low protein CNS

186
00:06:58.800 --> 00:07:01.170
and that could be why they had that Coumadin skin necrosis.

187
00:07:01.170 --> 00:07:03.870
So if someone gets that, test for that.

188
00:07:03.870 --> 00:07:06.330
I've put a list of all the things on here.

189
00:07:06.330 --> 00:07:08.190
They're not gonna test you on this on the board.

190
00:07:08.190 --> 00:07:10.500
This is for your clinical brain right here.

191
00:07:10.500 --> 00:07:13.560
But if they ask you a question about would you test them

192
00:07:13.560 --> 00:07:15.300
before starting treatment?

193
00:07:15.300 --> 00:07:16.680
The answer is yes.

194
00:07:16.680 --> 00:07:18.840
'Cause a lot of these tests are messed up.

195
00:07:18.840 --> 00:07:21.780
If you're already on a DOAC, or you're already on Coumadin.

196
00:07:21.780 --> 00:07:22.613
Okay?

197
00:07:22.613 --> 00:07:24.120
So try to get that testing done

198
00:07:24.120 --> 00:07:25.720
before you begin that treatment.

199
00:07:27.150 --> 00:07:28.740
Okay, next question here.

200
00:07:28.740 --> 00:07:31.800
63-year-old male presents with a history of several days

201
00:07:31.800 --> 00:07:33.390
of shortness of breath with exertion

202
00:07:33.390 --> 00:07:34.560
and pleuritic chest pain.

203
00:07:34.560 --> 00:07:36.630
He had a DVT five years ago.

204
00:07:36.630 --> 00:07:39.240
His O2 SAT is 85% on room air.

205
00:07:39.240 --> 00:07:40.650
Heart rate's one 10.

206
00:07:40.650 --> 00:07:43.260
He just returned from traveling to Japan.

207
00:07:43.260 --> 00:07:45.510
What is the best test for initial evaluation

208
00:07:45.510 --> 00:07:47.100
of this patient's symptoms?

209
00:07:47.100 --> 00:07:49.110
D-dimer, compression ultrasound

210
00:07:49.110 --> 00:07:52.683
of the lower extremities, a VQ scanning or CT angiography.

211
00:07:57.990 --> 00:07:58.920
Love it.

212
00:07:58.920 --> 00:07:59.753
CT angiography.

213
00:07:59.753 --> 00:08:00.794
So if we were an ER doctor,

214
00:08:00.794 --> 00:08:02.970
they'd be 100% 'cause they just love

215
00:08:02.970 --> 00:08:04.440
to get CTPAs.

216
00:08:04.440 --> 00:08:06.960
But in this case, this patient really does need a CTPA.

217
00:08:06.960 --> 00:08:09.180
And let's talk through why some of these other things

218
00:08:09.180 --> 00:08:11.100
aren't your first choice.

219
00:08:11.100 --> 00:08:12.270
PE is hard.

220
00:08:12.270 --> 00:08:15.360
The symptoms are pretty non-specific a lot of the times.

221
00:08:15.360 --> 00:08:17.130
You know we learned about in med school,

222
00:08:17.130 --> 00:08:21.450
oh, the EKG will show an S1, Q3, T3.

223
00:08:21.450 --> 00:08:23.670
Now, it usually just shows sinus attack,

224
00:08:23.670 --> 00:08:26.040
which can go with a million other things, right?

225
00:08:26.040 --> 00:08:28.770
The chest X-Ray will show a Hampton's hump.

226
00:08:28.770 --> 00:08:30.540
I've seen that once in 25 years.

227
00:08:30.540 --> 00:08:32.880
So probably not gonna see a Hampton's hump,

228
00:08:32.880 --> 00:08:36.960
that wedge shape, resection from a wedge shape infarction

229
00:08:36.960 --> 00:08:39.060
that can happen from a PE.

230
00:08:39.060 --> 00:08:40.770
And then normal O2 sat.

231
00:08:40.770 --> 00:08:43.230
You can't even hang your hat completely on that

232
00:08:43.230 --> 00:08:46.440
because if a normal O2 sat doesn't rule out a PE.

233
00:08:46.440 --> 00:08:47.880
It rules out a massive PE.

234
00:08:47.880 --> 00:08:50.040
but it doesn't rule out some smaller ones.

235
00:08:50.040 --> 00:08:52.170
So gosh, it's a hard diagnosis to make.

236
00:08:52.170 --> 00:08:55.140
So your clinical suspicion is really important here.

237
00:08:55.140 --> 00:08:56.790
This also has a Well's criteria.

238
00:08:56.790 --> 00:08:59.070
It's a little modified for PE,

239
00:08:59.070 --> 00:09:01.470
but it's been consistent for a long time.

240
00:09:01.470 --> 00:09:03.000
And if you look at our gentleman,

241
00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:04.860
he came up with 7 1/2 points.

242
00:09:04.860 --> 00:09:06.780
His other diagnosis is less likely

243
00:09:06.780 --> 00:09:09.240
'cause this sort of screamed PE to us.

244
00:09:09.240 --> 00:09:11.760
Heart rate was above 100 and he was immobilized

245
00:09:11.760 --> 00:09:13.740
because of his travel.

246
00:09:13.740 --> 00:09:17.100
So with that, he had some points going on.

247
00:09:17.100 --> 00:09:19.440
He also had that previous clot, 1.5 there.

248
00:09:19.440 --> 00:09:23.190
So high risk was his score being above six.

249
00:09:23.190 --> 00:09:27.960
So D-dimer, again, most helpful for a low probability test.

250
00:09:27.960 --> 00:09:30.990
If you already have a high probability, it's very reasonable

251
00:09:30.990 --> 00:09:34.530
to go straight to the CTPA and skip the D-dimer.

252
00:09:34.530 --> 00:09:37.860
There are some newer kind of recommendations coming out

253
00:09:37.860 --> 00:09:40.200
that, gosh, maybe we get too many CTPAs.

254
00:09:40.200 --> 00:09:41.700
I think that's a true statement.

255
00:09:41.700 --> 00:09:43.200
I have a person in my own practice

256
00:09:43.200 --> 00:09:45.480
who has a lot of panic disorder.

257
00:09:45.480 --> 00:09:47.460
Goes to the ER way too often.

258
00:09:47.460 --> 00:09:49.860
I'm embarrassed I can't get this under control for her.

259
00:09:49.860 --> 00:09:52.560
She's had 58 CTPAs.

260
00:09:52.560 --> 00:09:54.000
Holy smokes, right?

261
00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:55.200
That's a problem.

262
00:09:55.200 --> 00:09:57.487
So you're gonna start seeing some guidelines that say,

263
00:09:57.487 --> 00:09:59.670
"Gosh, maybe we should get D-dimers for everybody

264
00:09:59.670 --> 00:10:02.700
because we're way ordering too many of these in the ER."

265
00:10:02.700 --> 00:10:04.800
But if you really follow the Well's criteria,

266
00:10:04.800 --> 00:10:06.720
you wouldn't be ordering all those to begin with.

267
00:10:06.720 --> 00:10:08.970
So give that some thought.

268
00:10:08.970 --> 00:10:12.573
But negative D-dimer again, makes it very unlikely.

269
00:10:13.440 --> 00:10:15.990
CTPA is gonna be our test of choice here.

270
00:10:15.990 --> 00:10:17.970
High sensitivity and specificity,

271
00:10:17.970 --> 00:10:20.040
99% negative predictive value.

272
00:10:20.040 --> 00:10:21.840
So it's an excellent test.

273
00:10:21.840 --> 00:10:23.130
It is your test of choice

274
00:10:23.130 --> 00:10:25.200
if you have a low probability Well's

275
00:10:25.200 --> 00:10:27.180
but your D-dimer's positive.

276
00:10:27.180 --> 00:10:29.100
Or test of choice if you have a moderate

277
00:10:29.100 --> 00:10:30.870
or high pretest probability.

278
00:10:30.870 --> 00:10:33.390
You can go straight to the CTPA.

279
00:10:33.390 --> 00:10:35.430
Why don't we just angio everybody?

280
00:10:35.430 --> 00:10:36.960
Well because you could kill them accidentally.

281
00:10:36.960 --> 00:10:38.250
That would be unfortunate.

282
00:10:38.250 --> 00:10:40.680
2% mortality rate, 5% morbidity.

283
00:10:40.680 --> 00:10:43.410
So I haven't seen an angio done in a really long time

284
00:10:43.410 --> 00:10:46.050
'cause our CTPAs are really good tests.

285
00:10:46.050 --> 00:10:47.760
What about the old VQ scan?

286
00:10:47.760 --> 00:10:48.900
It's still a great test,

287
00:10:48.900 --> 00:10:51.060
we just don't see a lot of it anymore.

288
00:10:51.060 --> 00:10:52.980
But if you have a normal VQ,

289
00:10:52.980 --> 00:10:54.990
regardless of your pretest probability,

290
00:10:54.990 --> 00:10:57.420
you have ruled out a PE, you are done.

291
00:10:57.420 --> 00:11:01.770
If you have a low probability and a low probability VQ

292
00:11:01.770 --> 00:11:04.470
and a low pretest probability, you've excluded it,

293
00:11:04.470 --> 00:11:07.890
high probability with high pretest, you've ruled it in.

294
00:11:07.890 --> 00:11:09.843
Everybody else still needs a CTPA.

295
00:11:10.710 --> 00:11:13.230
So who do we really think about these in?

296
00:11:13.230 --> 00:11:16.080
If they have a contrast allergy can't tolerate a CTPA.

297
00:11:16.080 --> 00:11:18.060
If they have pretty severe renal disease

298
00:11:18.060 --> 00:11:21.030
greater than stage three, you think about this.

299
00:11:21.030 --> 00:11:22.968
Pregnancy is a consideration.

300
00:11:22.968 --> 00:11:24.270
The current guidelines

301
00:11:24.270 --> 00:11:25.530
say that if your institution

302
00:11:25.530 --> 00:11:28.020
only has a high dose CT scanner,

303
00:11:28.020 --> 00:11:29.580
then think about the VQ.

304
00:11:29.580 --> 00:11:31.860
If you have a traditional low dose CT scanner,

305
00:11:31.860 --> 00:11:34.500
which most institutions do now, it's acceptable

306
00:11:34.500 --> 00:11:35.973
to go straight to the CTPA.

307
00:11:37.260 --> 00:11:42.000
Here's that VQ scan look and abnormal there on the left.

308
00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:44.190
48-year-old female presents with three days

309
00:11:44.190 --> 00:11:46.440
of left lower extremity swelling.

310
00:11:46.440 --> 00:11:49.860
Venous doppler reveal proximal DVT, she's stable.

311
00:11:49.860 --> 00:11:51.180
No other medical conditions.

312
00:11:51.180 --> 00:11:53.580
What's gonna be our treatment of choice?

313
00:11:53.580 --> 00:11:55.980
Rivaroxaban only as an outpatient.

314
00:11:55.980 --> 00:11:58.680
Low molecular weight heparin for five days as a bridge

315
00:11:58.680 --> 00:12:01.050
to the rivaroxaban is outpatient.

316
00:12:01.050 --> 00:12:03.240
Hospitalization for unfractionated heparin

317
00:12:03.240 --> 00:12:04.710
and warfarin therapy.

318
00:12:04.710 --> 00:12:07.083
Or hospitalization for thrombolytic therapy.

319
00:12:12.360 --> 00:12:13.290
Good stuff.

320
00:12:13.290 --> 00:12:14.820
So this has been a change, right?

321
00:12:14.820 --> 00:12:16.350
We used to do a lot more Coumadin.

322
00:12:16.350 --> 00:12:18.030
Obviously, these DOACs, NOACs,

323
00:12:18.030 --> 00:12:19.438
have really taken over the world here.

324
00:12:19.438 --> 00:12:22.920
And Xarelto does not need a bridge.

325
00:12:22.920 --> 00:12:25.410
Some of them do and we'll talk about that.

326
00:12:25.410 --> 00:12:28.650
So DOACs are now preferred for treatment

327
00:12:28.650 --> 00:12:33.030
of venous thromboembolism, whether it's PE or DVT.

328
00:12:33.030 --> 00:12:34.170
The only exception to that

329
00:12:34.170 --> 00:12:36.180
is if you have a GI luminal cancer,

330
00:12:36.180 --> 00:12:37.860
and we'll talk about that in a moment.

331
00:12:37.860 --> 00:12:40.500
But for everybody else, DOACs are preferred.

332
00:12:40.500 --> 00:12:42.600
You're in the therapeutic window more often,

333
00:12:42.600 --> 00:12:44.100
you have less major bleeding

334
00:12:44.100 --> 00:12:45.840
and improved patient convenience.

335
00:12:45.840 --> 00:12:47.250
But CHEST guidelines don't really care

336
00:12:47.250 --> 00:12:48.240
about patient convenience.

337
00:12:48.240 --> 00:12:50.160
But those first two are major factors.

338
00:12:50.160 --> 00:12:52.200
So CHEST change their recommendation

339
00:12:52.200 --> 00:12:55.110
to say these are superior to Coumadin.

340
00:12:55.110 --> 00:12:57.603
That recommendation was changed in 2021.

341
00:12:58.830 --> 00:13:00.930
So we see the Xarelto and Eliquis

342
00:13:00.930 --> 00:13:02.520
are the most commonly used ones

343
00:13:02.520 --> 00:13:05.070
because you don't need to bridge them with Lovenox.

344
00:13:05.070 --> 00:13:07.140
But sometimes insurance will dictate

345
00:13:07.140 --> 00:13:08.670
that you use one of the other ones.

346
00:13:08.670 --> 00:13:10.950
Or if it's a self-pay patient,

347
00:13:10.950 --> 00:13:12.480
Sava is one of the cheaper ones.

348
00:13:12.480 --> 00:13:13.710
It's still very expensive.

349
00:13:13.710 --> 00:13:16.200
But sometimes, you'll have a patient on that for the cost

350
00:13:16.200 --> 00:13:19.150
and in which case, you'll need to bridge them with Lovenox.

351
00:13:20.340 --> 00:13:22.170
Remember, renal disease in these patients,

352
00:13:22.170 --> 00:13:24.000
they all need to be renal dosed.

353
00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.790
So just pull up an app to remind yourself of that.

354
00:13:26.790 --> 00:13:27.623
Okay?

355
00:13:28.680 --> 00:13:29.880
What if you can't afford these?

356
00:13:29.880 --> 00:13:31.350
Which is a common problem.

357
00:13:31.350 --> 00:13:34.530
Then low molecular weight bridge to a warfarin

358
00:13:34.530 --> 00:13:36.960
is still acceptable, it's just not preferred.

359
00:13:36.960 --> 00:13:38.940
So try the first thing with the DOAC.

360
00:13:38.940 --> 00:13:42.060
If you can't get that covered, then transition over there.

361
00:13:42.060 --> 00:13:43.680
Reversal agents for many now.

362
00:13:43.680 --> 00:13:45.510
So if somebody comes in with a major bleed,

363
00:13:45.510 --> 00:13:48.210
you can use a reversal agent, you can charcoal them,

364
00:13:48.210 --> 00:13:51.870
you can dialyze them all off if you're really in a pickle.

365
00:13:51.870 --> 00:13:55.170
Cancer associated thrombosis has been a recent change.

366
00:13:55.170 --> 00:13:58.110
CHEST guidelines used to say it's Lovenox for everybody

367
00:13:58.110 --> 00:14:01.080
if they have a cancer-associated clot.

368
00:14:01.080 --> 00:14:02.970
Data started coming out in 2019

369
00:14:02.970 --> 00:14:04.590
of like, "Hey, maybe that's not the case.

370
00:14:04.590 --> 00:14:06.240
Maybe these DOACs are pretty good."

371
00:14:06.240 --> 00:14:07.890
And actually, they are.

372
00:14:07.890 --> 00:14:10.590
And now they're recommended over Lovenox

373
00:14:10.590 --> 00:14:12.330
except for GI luminal cancers.

374
00:14:12.330 --> 00:14:14.790
For that specific type of cancer,

375
00:14:14.790 --> 00:14:16.830
your low molecular weight has better data.

376
00:14:16.830 --> 00:14:19.470
They have less hemorrhaging from that essentially.

377
00:14:19.470 --> 00:14:21.270
Coumadin is considered third line

378
00:14:21.270 --> 00:14:23.043
for cancer-associated clots.

379
00:14:24.660 --> 00:14:26.490
This is also kind of newer stuff.

380
00:14:26.490 --> 00:14:30.390
If you have an isolated distal DVT, so not a proximal

381
00:14:30.390 --> 00:14:34.590
but a distal DVT, you don't have to anticoagulate them.

382
00:14:34.590 --> 00:14:36.840
This is gonna take some, you know, informed consent

383
00:14:36.840 --> 00:14:38.160
with your patient of course,

384
00:14:38.160 --> 00:14:39.990
and you're gonna wanna make sure

385
00:14:39.990 --> 00:14:41.700
that you're following them every two weeks

386
00:14:41.700 --> 00:14:44.068
to make sure they're not propagating

387
00:14:44.068 --> 00:14:46.050
to a more proximal location.

388
00:14:46.050 --> 00:14:47.910
You also have to make sure they don't have

389
00:14:47.910 --> 00:14:50.370
any of these risk factors for extension listed here.

390
00:14:50.370 --> 00:14:52.980
So if it's a really big distal clot,

391
00:14:52.980 --> 00:14:54.840
I'm gonna anticoagulate that.

392
00:14:54.840 --> 00:14:56.610
If it's close to one of those bigger veins,

393
00:14:56.610 --> 00:14:58.350
I'm gonna anticoagulate that.

394
00:14:58.350 --> 00:15:01.230
If they have cancer, I'm gonna anticoagulate that.

395
00:15:01.230 --> 00:15:03.540
So it takes a special patient to not need it,

396
00:15:03.540 --> 00:15:05.610
but it is an acceptable thing in recommended

397
00:15:05.610 --> 00:15:08.580
per CHEST guidelines to just expectantly manage

398
00:15:08.580 --> 00:15:11.133
those isolated distal DVTs.

399
00:15:12.660 --> 00:15:14.910
Is it okay to treat them as an outpatient?

400
00:15:14.910 --> 00:15:16.100
Yes, and we talked about that

401
00:15:16.100 --> 00:15:18.000
in one of our earlier questions.

402
00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:20.310
So if you're ambulatory, you're not needing oxygen,

403
00:15:20.310 --> 00:15:22.890
you don't need IV meds, you're not on IV antibiotics,

404
00:15:22.890 --> 00:15:23.940
low risk of bleeding,

405
00:15:23.940 --> 00:15:26.370
renal insufficiency isn't such a big thing for you,

406
00:15:26.370 --> 00:15:28.440
that's a great outpatient candidate.

407
00:15:28.440 --> 00:15:29.850
Who needs to come in?

408
00:15:29.850 --> 00:15:32.730
If they have a massive DVT oftentimes for pain control,

409
00:15:32.730 --> 00:15:33.870
they'll need to come in.

410
00:15:33.870 --> 00:15:35.400
If they're a symptomatic PE,

411
00:15:35.400 --> 00:15:37.980
that's kind of a slam dunk, we're gonna bring those in.

412
00:15:37.980 --> 00:15:40.500
High risk for bleeding or other comorbid conditions,

413
00:15:40.500 --> 00:15:42.550
might need to bring them in the hospital.

414
00:15:43.470 --> 00:15:45.270
Duration of treatment, three months

415
00:15:45.270 --> 00:15:47.370
is your kinda money to hang your hat on.

416
00:15:47.370 --> 00:15:49.530
So if it is a provoked DVT

417
00:15:49.530 --> 00:15:52.740
and now we sort of call that transient risk factors.

418
00:15:52.740 --> 00:15:54.150
So that may mean surgery,

419
00:15:54.150 --> 00:15:56.400
that may mean I just traveled to Japan.

420
00:15:56.400 --> 00:15:58.230
That may mean I just had COVID.

421
00:15:58.230 --> 00:16:00.300
Those would be considered transient risk factors

422
00:16:00.300 --> 00:16:03.450
and three months is pretty clearly recommended for those.

423
00:16:03.450 --> 00:16:07.140
That's part of the hematology Choosing Wisely campaign.

424
00:16:07.140 --> 00:16:08.550
What if it was unprovoked

425
00:16:08.550 --> 00:16:11.670
or what we would consider a long-term risk factor?

426
00:16:11.670 --> 00:16:12.960
There's some debate on this,

427
00:16:12.960 --> 00:16:15.180
but three plus months is what's recommended.

428
00:16:15.180 --> 00:16:17.700
CHEST says at least three months.

429
00:16:17.700 --> 00:16:20.370
The ASH guidelines, American Society of Hematology

430
00:16:20.370 --> 00:16:21.630
says three to six.

431
00:16:21.630 --> 00:16:23.160
So you'll see a couple different numbers,

432
00:16:23.160 --> 00:16:25.650
but at least three, maybe longer.

433
00:16:25.650 --> 00:16:27.900
What is a grade 2B recommendation?

434
00:16:27.900 --> 00:16:29.610
Long term.

435
00:16:29.610 --> 00:16:31.380
If there's low risk of bleeding.

436
00:16:31.380 --> 00:16:33.660
If they're one of those higher risk of bleeding patients,

437
00:16:33.660 --> 00:16:35.430
which you can check on your MD calc

438
00:16:35.430 --> 00:16:37.920
with your has blood formula,

439
00:16:37.920 --> 00:16:39.510
then you would stop at three months.

440
00:16:39.510 --> 00:16:42.150
'cause at that point, the risk benefit ratio is not there

441
00:16:42.150 --> 00:16:43.890
and you would transition them to aspirin

442
00:16:43.890 --> 00:16:45.900
if they can tolerate that.

443
00:16:45.900 --> 00:16:48.660
If it's a recurrent DVT, then it's lifelong

444
00:16:48.660 --> 00:16:50.560
until their bleeding risk is too high.

445
00:16:51.720 --> 00:16:54.240
What about this catheter directed thrombolysis?

446
00:16:54.240 --> 00:16:56.670
We're starting to hear a little bit more about this.

447
00:16:56.670 --> 00:16:58.800
It is an adjunct to anticoagulation

448
00:16:58.800 --> 00:17:01.080
to reduce that clot burden faster.

449
00:17:01.080 --> 00:17:02.490
So you have less complications,

450
00:17:02.490 --> 00:17:04.980
less valve damage in the long run.

451
00:17:04.980 --> 00:17:06.060
The problem is we just need

452
00:17:06.060 --> 00:17:07.440
some randomized controlled trials.

453
00:17:07.440 --> 00:17:09.180
So I don't think you're gonna be tested on this,

454
00:17:09.180 --> 00:17:11.830
but just clinically I wanted you to be aware of that.

455
00:17:13.200 --> 00:17:15.960
What do we say about, we used to put everybody on bedrest

456
00:17:15.960 --> 00:17:17.880
and put them all on compression stockings.

457
00:17:17.880 --> 00:17:19.440
Those things are no longer recommended.

458
00:17:19.440 --> 00:17:20.610
They did not show benefit

459
00:17:20.610 --> 00:17:22.410
and those are also part of the hematology

460
00:17:22.410 --> 00:17:24.360
Choosing Wisely campaigns.

461
00:17:24.360 --> 00:17:26.070
So if you get long-term edema

462
00:17:26.070 --> 00:17:29.220
because of a DVT, you can use compression stockings there.

463
00:17:29.220 --> 00:17:30.840
But if you have a DVT today,

464
00:17:30.840 --> 00:17:33.900
starting compression stockings doesn't decrease your chances

465
00:17:33.900 --> 00:17:35.880
of having a long-term issue.

466
00:17:35.880 --> 00:17:36.713
Okay?

467
00:17:36.713 --> 00:17:40.053
So it does not decrease recurrent DVT or thrombophlebitis.

468
00:17:42.060 --> 00:17:43.080
What about PE?

469
00:17:43.080 --> 00:17:44.280
What's different?

470
00:17:44.280 --> 00:17:45.840
They oftentimes can be unstable.

471
00:17:45.840 --> 00:17:48.660
So if they have hemodynamic instability, hypotension,

472
00:17:48.660 --> 00:17:50.165
you need to think about a systemic thrombolytic

473
00:17:50.165 --> 00:17:51.810
in that patient.

474
00:17:51.810 --> 00:17:53.490
And for PE, again,

475
00:17:53.490 --> 00:17:56.280
because they're hard to diagnose if it's on your brain,

476
00:17:56.280 --> 00:17:58.650
just treat them while you're working it up.

477
00:17:58.650 --> 00:18:00.930
You know, give them a dose of Lovenox in the ER

478
00:18:00.930 --> 00:18:03.390
or urgent care even from your office

479
00:18:03.390 --> 00:18:06.030
while you're working them up if you need to.

480
00:18:06.030 --> 00:18:07.950
Who needs an IVC filter?

481
00:18:07.950 --> 00:18:10.530
Pretty much if you can't tolerate anticoagulants.

482
00:18:10.530 --> 00:18:14.100
Anticoagulation is much better but if you can't tolerate it,

483
00:18:14.100 --> 00:18:17.070
then IVC filters a reasonable choice for you.

484
00:18:17.070 --> 00:18:19.110
Do remember to remove that filter

485
00:18:19.110 --> 00:18:20.970
when your treatment window is up.

486
00:18:20.970 --> 00:18:21.803
Okay?

487
00:18:21.803 --> 00:18:23.190
80% can be removed.

488
00:18:23.190 --> 00:18:25.290
If you just kinda put it in and leave it there,

489
00:18:25.290 --> 00:18:28.090
you are gonna increase your risk of DVT in the long run.

490
00:18:30.030 --> 00:18:34.200
Just like we said, distal isolated DVTs don't need treated.

491
00:18:34.200 --> 00:18:38.430
Subsegmental PEs can also just be observed.

492
00:18:38.430 --> 00:18:41.643
That's a new recommendation that came out of CHEST in 2021.

493
00:18:43.020 --> 00:18:44.610
There are some guidelines here as well.

494
00:18:44.610 --> 00:18:46.890
You can't have proximal artery involvement.

495
00:18:46.890 --> 00:18:49.170
You can't have a proximal DVT in the leg

496
00:18:49.170 --> 00:18:50.790
'cause we would need to treat those anyway.

497
00:18:50.790 --> 00:18:53.400
And they shouldn't be a person with high risk of recurrence.

498
00:18:53.400 --> 00:18:55.050
Again, if this is a cancer patient,

499
00:18:55.050 --> 00:18:56.730
you're not gonna opt to not treat them.

500
00:18:56.730 --> 00:18:57.563
Okay?

501
00:18:57.563 --> 00:19:00.060
Again, informed consent, very important here.

502
00:19:00.060 --> 00:19:03.090
But they do recommend clinical surveillance is superior

503
00:19:03.090 --> 00:19:06.270
to anticoagulation if you meet all those parameters.

504
00:19:06.270 --> 00:19:08.430
All right, so what do we do if there's a pregnant person?

505
00:19:08.430 --> 00:19:11.730
28-year-old G3P2 is diagnosed

506
00:19:11.730 --> 00:19:13.440
with DVT in her right lower extremity.

507
00:19:13.440 --> 00:19:16.590
The treatment of choice for this patient would be apixaban,

508
00:19:16.590 --> 00:19:18.600
unfractionated heparin and warfarin,

509
00:19:18.600 --> 00:19:20.370
low molecular weight heparin

510
00:19:20.370 --> 00:19:21.783
or a vena cava filter.

511
00:19:26.610 --> 00:19:28.470
Low molecular weight heparin, excellent.

512
00:19:28.470 --> 00:19:31.170
92, 91% of you got that, love it.

513
00:19:31.170 --> 00:19:32.523
That is the right answer.

514
00:19:33.390 --> 00:19:35.640
You're definitely gonna see blood clots in pregnancy.

515
00:19:35.640 --> 00:19:38.733
It increases fivefold compared to general population.

516
00:19:39.720 --> 00:19:42.990
Overall risk is about one outta 1,600 pregnancies

517
00:19:42.990 --> 00:19:45.510
and PE is still a leading cause of morbidity

518
00:19:45.510 --> 00:19:47.640
and mortality in pregnancy.

519
00:19:47.640 --> 00:19:50.460
Up to half of those can have an underlying thrombophilia.

520
00:19:50.460 --> 00:19:52.110
So we already mentioned that some things

521
00:19:52.110 --> 00:19:54.270
can lower your protein CNS.

522
00:19:54.270 --> 00:19:56.520
pregnancy is one that can do that.

523
00:19:56.520 --> 00:19:58.140
So that is already gonna be low,

524
00:19:58.140 --> 00:20:01.560
but you might have a secondary thrombophilia on top of it.

525
00:20:01.560 --> 00:20:02.700
If you've had one before,

526
00:20:02.700 --> 00:20:04.590
you've got up to a four times higher chance

527
00:20:04.590 --> 00:20:05.733
of having one again.

528
00:20:07.260 --> 00:20:09.840
Overall, the risk of clots DVT

529
00:20:09.840 --> 00:20:11.550
and PE together are pretty equal.

530
00:20:11.550 --> 00:20:13.380
Antepartum and postpartum pretty equal

531
00:20:13.380 --> 00:20:15.000
throughout the trimesters.

532
00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:18.900
If you pull out just PE though, that's a postpartum thing.

533
00:20:18.900 --> 00:20:22.740
Much more PE in that first week to 10 days after delivery.

534
00:20:22.740 --> 00:20:25.140
So keep that a little higher on your radar

535
00:20:25.140 --> 00:20:28.170
if you're seeing them back for unrelated things.

536
00:20:28.170 --> 00:20:29.970
D-dimer is still a great test,

537
00:20:29.970 --> 00:20:31.590
but oh, it's almost always positive

538
00:20:31.590 --> 00:20:35.340
in the prepartum period of time.

539
00:20:35.340 --> 00:20:37.173
So not so helpful.

540
00:20:38.160 --> 00:20:41.460
Low dose CTPAs, as we mentioned, are safe in pregnancy.

541
00:20:41.460 --> 00:20:45.750
And so if you only have a high dose option available to you,

542
00:20:45.750 --> 00:20:48.330
ACOG recommends you do chest X-Ray first.

543
00:20:48.330 --> 00:20:49.920
If the chest X-Ray is normal,

544
00:20:49.920 --> 00:20:52.350
then you have an option of getting that VQ.

545
00:20:52.350 --> 00:20:54.510
If you have a baseline abnormal chest X-Ray,

546
00:20:54.510 --> 00:20:56.280
the VQ is not an option for you.

547
00:20:56.280 --> 00:20:57.510
So you would have no choice

548
00:20:57.510 --> 00:21:00.933
but to do a high dose CAT scan if that was your only option.

549
00:21:02.070 --> 00:21:04.290
It takes a whole lot of rads to injure a baby.

550
00:21:04.290 --> 00:21:05.370
So you're not gonna get in trouble

551
00:21:05.370 --> 00:21:08.220
with, you know, even a single high dose CTPA.

552
00:21:08.220 --> 00:21:09.840
It takes a lot of them, but certainly,

553
00:21:09.840 --> 00:21:12.123
we still want to decrease radiation exposure.

554
00:21:13.110 --> 00:21:15.450
Anticoagulation in pregnancy says heparin

555
00:21:15.450 --> 00:21:17.730
and low molecular weight heparin are safe.

556
00:21:17.730 --> 00:21:19.980
Strength of recommendation B.

557
00:21:19.980 --> 00:21:22.320
We know that unfractionated heparin,

558
00:21:22.320 --> 00:21:24.300
the dose changes a lot more with that one.

559
00:21:24.300 --> 00:21:26.730
So we use the low molecular weight heparin.

560
00:21:26.730 --> 00:21:28.800
There's data in non-pregnant people

561
00:21:28.800 --> 00:21:30.750
that low molecular weight heparin is better

562
00:21:30.750 --> 00:21:32.100
'cause of less bleeding.

563
00:21:32.100 --> 00:21:34.800
We don't have much of those data in pregnancy.

564
00:21:34.800 --> 00:21:37.710
We don't test a lot of pregnant women for things.

565
00:21:37.710 --> 00:21:40.500
They do have less HIIT heparin induced thrombocytopenia

566
00:21:40.500 --> 00:21:41.790
with low molecular weight heparin.

567
00:21:41.790 --> 00:21:43.320
So that's your advantage.

568
00:21:43.320 --> 00:21:45.810
Has a longer half-life, which is great for dosing.

569
00:21:45.810 --> 00:21:48.420
Not so great if you're trying to get an epidural though.

570
00:21:48.420 --> 00:21:50.280
You need to have about 12 hours distance

571
00:21:50.280 --> 00:21:52.170
between your last Lovenox dose to get

572
00:21:52.170 --> 00:21:54.090
any kind of a spinal anesthesia.

573
00:21:54.090 --> 00:21:55.790
That's just expert opinion though.

574
00:21:56.880 --> 00:21:59.940
Warfarin is a no-no, I think we already know that.

575
00:21:59.940 --> 00:22:02.550
There are occasionally mechanical valve patients

576
00:22:02.550 --> 00:22:05.100
who are pregnant that might need to be on Coumadin.

577
00:22:05.100 --> 00:22:06.600
Those are not gonna be in your practice.

578
00:22:06.600 --> 00:22:08.460
So those are seeing a very high risk doctor

579
00:22:08.460 --> 00:22:09.570
and they can handle that.

580
00:22:09.570 --> 00:22:11.580
That's not something I would ever do.

581
00:22:11.580 --> 00:22:14.220
DOACs have just not been studied in pregnancy.

582
00:22:14.220 --> 00:22:16.170
So I'm hoping five, 10 years from now,

583
00:22:16.170 --> 00:22:17.760
we'll find that they're safe.

584
00:22:17.760 --> 00:22:19.650
We just don't know that answer yet.

585
00:22:19.650 --> 00:22:21.960
For breastfeeding, Coumadin

586
00:22:21.960 --> 00:22:24.030
and low molecular weight heparin have great evidence

587
00:22:24.030 --> 00:22:25.410
years and years of data.

588
00:22:25.410 --> 00:22:28.360
DOACs, there's limited data but we believe them to be safe.

589
00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:31.170
You can have this option

590
00:22:31.170 --> 00:22:32.820
of converting from low molecular weight

591
00:22:32.820 --> 00:22:36.180
to unfractionated heparin in that last month of pregnancy.

592
00:22:36.180 --> 00:22:37.641
Just so you don't interfere

593
00:22:37.641 --> 00:22:40.890
with any of your anesthesia products.

594
00:22:40.890 --> 00:22:42.642
When can you restart things after?

595
00:22:42.642 --> 00:22:45.270
About six hours after a vaginal birth,

596
00:22:45.270 --> 00:22:48.180
six to 12 hours after a C-section.

597
00:22:48.180 --> 00:22:50.220
And again, remember that bridging.

598
00:22:50.220 --> 00:22:53.760
If you are using postpartum Coumadin bridge with Lovenox,

599
00:22:53.760 --> 00:22:57.510
it's very essential 'cause of their already low protein CNS.

600
00:22:57.510 --> 00:22:59.250
What about if they've had COVID?

601
00:22:59.250 --> 00:23:02.070
If they've had COVID and are hospitalized, you do need

602
00:23:02.070 --> 00:23:04.200
to do prophylaxis while they're hospitalized

603
00:23:04.200 --> 00:23:06.510
and for two weeks after discharge.

604
00:23:06.510 --> 00:23:08.460
There is no data on doing that

605
00:23:08.460 --> 00:23:10.710
for an outpatient pregnant person who has COVID.

606
00:23:10.710 --> 00:23:12.330
If they're not sick enough to be in the hospital,

607
00:23:12.330 --> 00:23:14.610
there's no data on anticoagulation.

608
00:23:14.610 --> 00:23:16.320
We'll see some OBGYNs doing it,

609
00:23:16.320 --> 00:23:18.520
but the ACOG says you don't have to do that.

610
00:23:19.440 --> 00:23:20.490
What about estrogen?

611
00:23:20.490 --> 00:23:22.890
Can I use estrogen as a form of birth control

612
00:23:22.890 --> 00:23:23.760
if you've had a clot?

613
00:23:23.760 --> 00:23:25.200
The answer is no.

614
00:23:25.200 --> 00:23:26.119
What about progesterones?

615
00:23:26.119 --> 00:23:28.650
It's a little more controversial.

616
00:23:28.650 --> 00:23:31.740
NIH says okay, if you've had only one, you can do it.

617
00:23:31.740 --> 00:23:33.690
But if you've had more than one, no.

618
00:23:33.690 --> 00:23:35.940
And if you're gonna do it, maybe we don't use depo

619
00:23:35.940 --> 00:23:38.340
'cause potentially, that has a little higher risk

620
00:23:38.340 --> 00:23:39.960
of clot potential.

621
00:23:39.960 --> 00:23:41.730
All right, you guys are doing great.

622
00:23:41.730 --> 00:23:42.900
We're switching gears here.

623
00:23:42.900 --> 00:23:45.330
48-year-old female with rheumatoid arthritis

624
00:23:45.330 --> 00:23:46.620
presents to your office complaining

625
00:23:46.620 --> 00:23:49.470
of two months of fatigue, dyspnea on exertion.

626
00:23:49.470 --> 00:23:52.530
Hemoglobin's 9.2, normochromic, normocytic.

627
00:23:52.530 --> 00:23:54.840
You order iron studies which show low iron,

628
00:23:54.840 --> 00:23:57.390
low TIBC, high ferritin.

629
00:23:57.390 --> 00:23:59.610
What's the best treatment for this patient?

630
00:23:59.610 --> 00:24:03.900
Oral B12 for fatigue, oral ferrous sulfate for anemia,

631
00:24:03.900 --> 00:24:05.970
home oxygen for dyspnea

632
00:24:05.970 --> 00:24:08.460
or disease modifying anti rheumatic drugs

633
00:24:08.460 --> 00:24:10.083
for rheumatoid arthritis.

634
00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:15.833
Okay, good.

635
00:24:15.833 --> 00:24:16.980
Most of you got this right.

636
00:24:16.980 --> 00:24:19.080
If the boards ever give you an option

637
00:24:19.080 --> 00:24:22.050
to treat the underlying disease, choose that option.

638
00:24:22.050 --> 00:24:23.160
And so that's the case here.

639
00:24:23.160 --> 00:24:26.040
Treat the underlying rheumatoid arthritis.

640
00:24:26.040 --> 00:24:27.390
So when we think about anemia,

641
00:24:27.390 --> 00:24:29.010
there's sort of two ways to think about it.

642
00:24:29.010 --> 00:24:30.810
You can think about the kinetic approach,

643
00:24:30.810 --> 00:24:33.300
which is why are they getting anemia?

644
00:24:33.300 --> 00:24:35.100
Maybe they're not making enough of it.

645
00:24:35.100 --> 00:24:37.380
A hint there would be your reticulocyte index

646
00:24:37.380 --> 00:24:38.700
would be under two.

647
00:24:38.700 --> 00:24:41.550
Or maybe they're losing that blood somewhere.

648
00:24:41.550 --> 00:24:42.810
They could be hemolyzing it.

649
00:24:42.810 --> 00:24:43.643
If that's the case,

650
00:24:43.643 --> 00:24:46.200
your reticulocyte index would be over two

651
00:24:46.200 --> 00:24:48.450
or maybe it's just a blood loss.

652
00:24:48.450 --> 00:24:50.460
Well lots of times, I don't know why they're losing it.

653
00:24:50.460 --> 00:24:52.470
So then you use this morphologic approach

654
00:24:52.470 --> 00:24:54.690
and that's where your indices on your CBC

655
00:24:54.690 --> 00:24:57.210
can direct your management.

656
00:24:57.210 --> 00:24:58.830
MCV is kind of your money here.

657
00:24:58.830 --> 00:25:01.770
So I talked about reticulocyte index being really important.

658
00:25:01.770 --> 00:25:04.140
MCB is really important too,

659
00:25:04.140 --> 00:25:05.880
and that basically will just help direct

660
00:25:05.880 --> 00:25:07.530
what type of anemia we're talking about.

661
00:25:07.530 --> 00:25:12.530
So macrocytic, MCB over 100, you'll see reticulocytosis.

662
00:25:13.620 --> 00:25:16.350
That says that your body realizes you're low on blood.

663
00:25:16.350 --> 00:25:19.140
So it starts kicking out immature red blood cells,

664
00:25:19.140 --> 00:25:20.940
which are those big round beefy ones.

665
00:25:20.940 --> 00:25:23.820
They haven't became like those biconcave discs yet.

666
00:25:23.820 --> 00:25:27.390
So the RDW, red cell distribution width will be higher.

667
00:25:27.390 --> 00:25:29.610
This is your body saying, "Hey, I've identified it,

668
00:25:29.610 --> 00:25:30.720
I'm doing something about it.

669
00:25:30.720 --> 00:25:33.570
So you know there's some chronicity with this."

670
00:25:33.570 --> 00:25:36.270
This shows up on the boards over and over and over and over.

671
00:25:36.270 --> 00:25:40.080
B12 deficiency, folate deficiency fall within this category

672
00:25:40.080 --> 00:25:43.530
and PPIs and metformin can cause B12 deficiency.

673
00:25:43.530 --> 00:25:46.130
So that's a common thing that they'll ask you about.

674
00:25:47.070 --> 00:25:49.953
Alcohol abuse is also a common one in this category.

675
00:25:51.150 --> 00:25:53.250
Microcytic anemia on the flip side of that.

676
00:25:53.250 --> 00:25:54.600
MCV less than 80,

677
00:25:54.600 --> 00:25:56.910
this is usually your iron deficiency patients.

678
00:25:56.910 --> 00:25:59.940
You can also see lead, sideroblastic anemia here.

679
00:25:59.940 --> 00:26:02.940
Rarely, you can see this as a chronic anemia,

680
00:26:02.940 --> 00:26:04.950
like anemia of chronic disease,

681
00:26:04.950 --> 00:26:07.560
but usually anemia of chronic disease is this one.

682
00:26:07.560 --> 00:26:10.110
Normal chronic normocytic anemia.

683
00:26:10.110 --> 00:26:12.390
Also in this category is acute blood loss,

684
00:26:12.390 --> 00:26:15.540
acute hemolysis and hypersplenism.

685
00:26:15.540 --> 00:26:18.210
So just a couple words on iron deficiency anemia.

686
00:26:18.210 --> 00:26:20.310
What would your iron studies look like?

687
00:26:20.310 --> 00:26:23.280
Low iron, high iron binding capacity,

688
00:26:23.280 --> 00:26:25.740
high TIBC, and low ferritin.

689
00:26:25.740 --> 00:26:27.900
That's why the person in this one shouldn't have just gotten

690
00:26:27.900 --> 00:26:31.020
the iron that some of you recommended.

691
00:26:31.020 --> 00:26:33.600
They had a low iron binding capacity.

692
00:26:33.600 --> 00:26:36.003
So that is not consistent with iron deficiency.

693
00:26:36.900 --> 00:26:38.010
Iron deficiency anemia

694
00:26:38.010 --> 00:26:39.630
really should be kind of like a symptom,

695
00:26:39.630 --> 00:26:40.920
not a final diagnosis.

696
00:26:40.920 --> 00:26:42.210
You must figure out why.

697
00:26:42.210 --> 00:26:43.620
You can't just leave that on your chart

698
00:26:43.620 --> 00:26:45.090
and feel good about it.

699
00:26:45.090 --> 00:26:46.470
Are they having menstrual blood loss?

700
00:26:46.470 --> 00:26:49.470
Is there an occult GI bleed that you don't know about

701
00:26:49.470 --> 00:26:52.380
If you think you've solved the mystery and they're on iron,

702
00:26:52.380 --> 00:26:53.910
one of the quickest ways to test

703
00:26:53.910 --> 00:26:55.770
and actually the board's like this.

704
00:26:55.770 --> 00:26:58.800
If you test in just one week, that reticulocyte count,

705
00:26:58.800 --> 00:27:00.360
it should normalize within a week.

706
00:27:00.360 --> 00:27:01.620
If they're no longer bleeding

707
00:27:01.620 --> 00:27:03.090
and they're taking their iron.

708
00:27:03.090 --> 00:27:05.070
If it isn't normalizing, you might still need

709
00:27:05.070 --> 00:27:07.710
to be hunting down the source of the issue.

710
00:27:07.710 --> 00:27:09.750
Hematocrit won't correct itself for about a month,

711
00:27:09.750 --> 00:27:12.060
month and a half, and your total iron stores

712
00:27:12.060 --> 00:27:13.830
won't correct for six months.

713
00:27:13.830 --> 00:27:16.350
So I think this is another mistake that we sometimes make.

714
00:27:16.350 --> 00:27:17.880
You know, they'll have a GI bleed,

715
00:27:17.880 --> 00:27:20.996
we see them back in a month, we check their blood counts,

716
00:27:20.996 --> 00:27:22.290
they look great, we stop iron.

717
00:27:22.290 --> 00:27:24.450
You still have a total storage depletion.

718
00:27:24.450 --> 00:27:26.523
So continue that iron for six months.

719
00:27:27.360 --> 00:27:29.190
Low dose, just as effective.

720
00:27:29.190 --> 00:27:31.680
We no longer need to do the 325 TID

721
00:27:31.680 --> 00:27:33.390
like maybe we were trained on.

722
00:27:33.390 --> 00:27:36.150
Low dose is fine, even every other day is fine.

723
00:27:36.150 --> 00:27:37.593
That's just expert opinion.

724
00:27:38.550 --> 00:27:40.440
Another gear swift shift here.

725
00:27:40.440 --> 00:27:41.970
Three-year-old patients brought to you

726
00:27:41.970 --> 00:27:43.140
after moving to your community.

727
00:27:43.140 --> 00:27:47.040
He has SS disease, hemoglobin SS disease.

728
00:27:47.040 --> 00:27:48.300
Parents wanna know if he still needs

729
00:27:48.300 --> 00:27:51.180
to be taking his prophylactic penicillin.

730
00:27:51.180 --> 00:27:52.410
Should you stop the penicillin

731
00:27:52.410 --> 00:27:54.300
to avoid antibiotic resistance?

732
00:27:54.300 --> 00:27:57.480
Take 125 daily for the rest of his life.

733
00:27:57.480 --> 00:28:01.020
Take two 50 BID until five years of age at least,

734
00:28:01.020 --> 00:28:03.273
or take 250 until age 12.

735
00:28:08.640 --> 00:28:10.950
But look how smart you guys are with test taking.

736
00:28:10.950 --> 00:28:12.450
Again, if you knew nothing else,

737
00:28:12.450 --> 00:28:14.460
look at the things that look similar.

738
00:28:14.460 --> 00:28:15.960
Two of them say 250.

739
00:28:15.960 --> 00:28:18.120
So if I don't know anything else, I'm gonna say that.

740
00:28:18.120 --> 00:28:21.090
And one of them said till age five at least.

741
00:28:21.090 --> 00:28:22.350
Oh, that sounds pretty good

742
00:28:22.350 --> 00:28:24.780
'cause that could even be up to 12 'cause it's at least.

743
00:28:24.780 --> 00:28:28.203
So just from test taking, C is the right answer.

744
00:28:29.130 --> 00:28:30.570
So what do we need to know about this?

745
00:28:30.570 --> 00:28:34.080
Occasionally, they'll ask you about a sickle SC disease.

746
00:28:34.080 --> 00:28:36.750
Remember that that has less severe disease overall

747
00:28:36.750 --> 00:28:38.100
but more retinal disease.

748
00:28:38.100 --> 00:28:40.620
So sometimes, they'll talk about eye symptoms there.

749
00:28:40.620 --> 00:28:42.270
Sickle-Thal can be all over the map.

750
00:28:42.270 --> 00:28:45.690
It just depends on how much fetal hemoglobin you have.

751
00:28:45.690 --> 00:28:48.000
Important clinical manifestations here.

752
00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:49.890
Low hemoglobin, we're talking less than eight.

753
00:28:49.890 --> 00:28:51.690
And all these vaso-occlusive crisis,

754
00:28:51.690 --> 00:28:54.390
which is what we see them in the hospital for.

755
00:28:54.390 --> 00:28:56.240
If they're having a pain crisis, it's strength

756
00:28:56.240 --> 00:29:00.750
of recommendation B, to use IV narcotics for severe pain,

757
00:29:00.750 --> 00:29:03.300
and to use NSAIDs for mild to moderate pain.

758
00:29:03.300 --> 00:29:04.800
I think sometimes we get in a cycle

759
00:29:04.800 --> 00:29:06.750
of just everybody getting on IV narcotics.

760
00:29:06.750 --> 00:29:07.830
If they're a sickle patient

761
00:29:07.830 --> 00:29:10.170
and that's not necessarily supported.

762
00:29:10.170 --> 00:29:11.280
Give them all the vaccines

763
00:29:11.280 --> 00:29:12.810
and give them some of the extra ones.

764
00:29:12.810 --> 00:29:15.360
They're ones that get the PREVNAR 20 early.

765
00:29:15.360 --> 00:29:18.273
They're also ones that get the MenB early, okay?

766
00:29:19.350 --> 00:29:21.270
The prophylaxis is here.

767
00:29:21.270 --> 00:29:22.710
There's data up to age five.

768
00:29:22.710 --> 00:29:24.303
After that, it's controversial.

769
00:29:25.830 --> 00:29:27.570
This was recently tested on.

770
00:29:27.570 --> 00:29:30.630
Annual screening with the transcranial doppler ultrasound

771
00:29:30.630 --> 00:29:32.220
to evaluate for the risk of stroke

772
00:29:32.220 --> 00:29:34.860
between the ages of two and 16.

773
00:29:34.860 --> 00:29:36.660
That's strength of recommendation A,

774
00:29:36.660 --> 00:29:37.950
that's really big information.

775
00:29:37.950 --> 00:29:40.260
So if you do have any sickle cell patients in your practice,

776
00:29:40.260 --> 00:29:41.610
that needs to be happening.

777
00:29:42.510 --> 00:29:45.180
Hydroxyurea, strength of recommendation B

778
00:29:45.180 --> 00:29:47.640
because it is a disease modifying agent.

779
00:29:47.640 --> 00:29:48.473
Okay?

780
00:29:48.473 --> 00:29:50.070
And you can see the age ranges here,

781
00:29:50.070 --> 00:29:53.370
kids nine to 42 months or adults who are having three

782
00:29:53.370 --> 00:29:54.843
or more crisis in a year.

783
00:29:56.790 --> 00:29:58.890
Very quickly on multiple myeloma.

784
00:29:58.890 --> 00:30:00.240
We know that this is a disease.

785
00:30:00.240 --> 00:30:01.410
More of those who are elder.

786
00:30:01.410 --> 00:30:05.100
This is a more a common thing in our Black patients.

787
00:30:05.100 --> 00:30:07.950
It's 10% of hematologic cancers overall.

788
00:30:07.950 --> 00:30:10.050
Anemia, bone pain, and elevated creatinine

789
00:30:10.050 --> 00:30:12.423
are the classic triad for this.

790
00:30:13.320 --> 00:30:15.750
Here's some of the workup things that you may need to do,

791
00:30:15.750 --> 00:30:18.690
but this is what was recently on a board.

792
00:30:18.690 --> 00:30:22.110
Bisphosphonate treatment at the time of diagnosis.

793
00:30:22.110 --> 00:30:23.610
That's a primary care thing.

794
00:30:23.610 --> 00:30:25.560
Their hematologist may or not be doing that,

795
00:30:25.560 --> 00:30:27.360
but you need to be doing that.

796
00:30:27.360 --> 00:30:30.900
DVT prevention, that also falls to us.

797
00:30:30.900 --> 00:30:31.890
Low molecular weight.

798
00:30:31.890 --> 00:30:33.990
Heparin was the treatment of choice before,

799
00:30:33.990 --> 00:30:36.930
now DOACs have also been felt to be appropriate for that.

800
00:30:36.930 --> 00:30:39.750
So either one, whatever you can get covered is fine.

801
00:30:39.750 --> 00:30:41.310
They do need infection prevention

802
00:30:41.310 --> 00:30:42.780
with prophylactic antibiotics

803
00:30:42.780 --> 00:30:44.850
for that first three months of treatment.

804
00:30:44.850 --> 00:30:47.343
And they do need all the vaccines as well.

805
00:30:49.320 --> 00:30:51.660
Hemophilia, very, very briefly.

806
00:30:51.660 --> 00:30:54.330
Remember that only 50% have bleeding

807
00:30:54.330 --> 00:30:55.560
at the time of circumcision.

808
00:30:55.560 --> 00:30:57.420
So that doesn't mean you're totally out of the woods

809
00:30:57.420 --> 00:30:59.340
as they didn't bleed at the circ.

810
00:30:59.340 --> 00:31:02.043
5% will have bleeding still in the prenatal period.

811
00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:05.190
Joints are a big issue for these patients.

812
00:31:05.190 --> 00:31:07.200
If they have bleeding into a joint space,

813
00:31:07.200 --> 00:31:09.750
they have very early and progressive arthritis,

814
00:31:09.750 --> 00:31:11.670
which can be very debilitating.

815
00:31:11.670 --> 00:31:13.680
So using factor concentrate

816
00:31:13.680 --> 00:31:15.993
can really be disease modifying for them.

817
00:31:17.310 --> 00:31:20.310
TTP, very briefly, here's the five things

818
00:31:20.310 --> 00:31:21.750
that involve the TTP.

819
00:31:21.750 --> 00:31:23.670
Most patients don't have all of those things.

820
00:31:23.670 --> 00:31:25.380
Some will only have a few.

821
00:31:25.380 --> 00:31:28.020
If they have really pronounced renal insufficiency,

822
00:31:28.020 --> 00:31:30.810
that's probably in the hemolytic uremic syndrome,

823
00:31:30.810 --> 00:31:33.450
which is kind of this, if there's a continuation of this.

824
00:31:33.450 --> 00:31:35.970
If it's really strong neurologic symptoms,

825
00:31:35.970 --> 00:31:37.830
TTP is gonna be more likely.

826
00:31:37.830 --> 00:31:39.720
If you're only seeing the platelet issue, right?

827
00:31:39.720 --> 00:31:41.553
That's ITP that we're worried about.

828
00:31:43.050 --> 00:31:47.610
ADAMTS13 deficiency did show up on an ITE recently.

829
00:31:47.610 --> 00:31:48.870
That's a tricky one.

830
00:31:48.870 --> 00:31:52.110
So it is a protease of Von Willebrand's Factor

831
00:31:52.110 --> 00:31:54.240
and it's an inhibitory autoantibody.

832
00:31:54.240 --> 00:31:57.030
So if you don't have enough ADAMTS13,

833
00:31:57.030 --> 00:31:59.460
you don't break down things like you're supposed to.

834
00:31:59.460 --> 00:32:01.890
So you end up with these really long polymers

835
00:32:01.890 --> 00:32:04.230
of Von Willebrand's that attracts a bunch of platelets

836
00:32:04.230 --> 00:32:06.450
and it messes up your platelet counts.

837
00:32:06.450 --> 00:32:07.607
E.coli can do this as well.

838
00:32:07.607 --> 00:32:10.530
'cause of the shiga toxin and Plavix.

839
00:32:10.530 --> 00:32:11.700
That's probably the most common

840
00:32:11.700 --> 00:32:13.470
'cause we see of TTP nowadays,

841
00:32:13.470 --> 00:32:16.440
clopidogrel 'cause so many patients are on that.

842
00:32:16.440 --> 00:32:18.720
Treatment, avoid the offending agent, stop it.

843
00:32:18.720 --> 00:32:21.060
And then plasma exchange.

844
00:32:21.060 --> 00:32:21.893
Leukemia.

845
00:32:21.893 --> 00:32:23.610
The only thing they usually test us on here

846
00:32:23.610 --> 00:32:26.760
is it'll be a kid who has fever and bleeding.

847
00:32:26.760 --> 00:32:28.500
Think about leukemia.

848
00:32:28.500 --> 00:32:31.290
For an adult, they're usually asymptomatic

849
00:32:31.290 --> 00:32:33.060
for those chronic leukemias.

850
00:32:33.060 --> 00:32:36.300
You'll just find it incidentally with leukocytosis on a CBC

851
00:32:36.300 --> 00:32:38.010
that you check for something else.

852
00:32:38.010 --> 00:32:40.410
The workup, this was on an ITE.

853
00:32:40.410 --> 00:32:43.793
Repeat the CBC, do a smear, check a flow cytometry,

854
00:32:43.793 --> 00:32:45.633
and get them off to oncology.

855
00:32:47.160 --> 00:32:47.993
You guys did it.

856
00:32:47.993 --> 00:32:49.230
That was a lot of stuff to cover.

857
00:32:49.230 --> 00:32:51.510
Here's your thing for your study folder

858
00:32:51.510 --> 00:32:53.550
and I again appreciate your attention today.

859
00:32:53.550 --> 00:32:55.213
<v Host>Thank you very much, Dr. Holt.</v>

860
00:32:55.213 --> 00:32:57.294
(audience applauding)

861
